post_text:
üçé Free School Meals Update

We are excited to announce that starting Monday, September 14, the cost of school breakfast and lunch for all students in Ankeny will be waived.

All full meals served inside the school as well as at curbside will be no charge. A la carte items or second entrees will only be sold in school and will be charged at their set prices.

Please note that FREE school meals will continue as long as funding is available, or through December 31, 2020.

Parents, be on the lookout for an email with more details that will be sent out this evening.

You can read the full update here: https://www.ankenyschools.org/news/2020/09/free-school-meals/

As the days leading up to school become increasingly more complex, Ankeny Schools is still moving forward with our back to school work. Today, we welcome new teachers to Ankeny!

Our teachers today were charged to "Be the One". We asked them to consider the following: "Community can be built every day, in every interaction with another person, when you listen, bridge differences, and embrace healthy conflict. Know what kind of community you want to be a part of and to create, then move to build it." Onward, by Elena Aguilar (2018)

Please join us in welcoming our new teachers to Ankeny Schools!

We are now accepting donations for masks and face shields!

To make a donation, we ask that you first set up an appointment with our Community Engagement Department in the district office. You can reach them at 515-289-3960.

We are accepting purchased and homemade masks in child and adult sizes. We prefer mask donations to be individually bagged, prewashed, and labeled with their size. We will also be accepting face shields.

Monetary donations can be made at this link: https://ia-ankeny-lite.intouchreceipting.com/
To donate, go to the drop down menu on the left side and select COVID-19 Donation and enter the amount desired. Then click the cart and complete the payment information.

We're pleased to share that our Grab and Go Meals will be continuing through August 21! üçé The process to pick up these meals will remain the same.

Here are those details:

Grab and Go meals will continue to be provided every Monday and Wednesday from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. Meals will be served at Northview Middle School and Ankeny High School.

As before, on Mondays breakfast and lunch will be distributed for Monday and Tuesday of that week. On Wednesdays breakfast and lunch will be distributed for Wednesday, Thursday and Friday of that week. Children do not need to be present to receive these meals.

Thank you to our Nutrition Services Team for all that they do!

Save the Date! üìÖ

On Saturday, August 8 from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m. and Sunday, August 9 from 11 a.m. to 2 p.m., Project Fresh Start and the Ankeny Community School District will be holding this year‚Äôs Days of Giving event at Prairie Ridge Middle School. This event provides students of Ankeny and Ankeny Christian Academy (grades k-12) with free school supplies and backpacks. The first year it existed, the group gave backpacks and supplies to 191 students. In 2019, Project Fresh Start distributed 784 backpacks and supplies.

This year will look a bit different to ensure the safety of our families and volunteers, so all supplies will be delivered directly to your vehicle.

Stay tuned for more details to come!

Grab and Go meals will continue to be provided from July 1 through Wednesday, August 21 every Monday and Wednesday from 12 p.m. to 1 p.m. Meals will be served at Northview Middle School and Ankeny High School.

Kylie Kinzie, an 8th grader from Northview Middle School, recently received both 4th and 5th place for her posters in the 2020 Iowa Radon Poster Contest!

252 posters from twelve Iowa schools were submitted to Iowa's contest. Kylie was the only Iowa student to have two posters place in the top five!

Her posters will be featured on the American Lung Association website in the future, and Kylie received two scholarships for her creative work. Congratulations, Kylie! üëè

In April, the World Food Prize Foundation held their first virtual Iowa Youth Institute. The Youth Institutes convene high school students, teachers and experts to explore and solve local, national and global hunger and food security issues. In order to be a part of the Iowa Youth Institute, students research and write a paper on a global challenge related to hunger and food insecurity. 264 students and 110 teachers from 93 Iowa high schools took part in this unique experience.

The Ankeny Community School District was proudly represented by twenty-two total students from Northview Middle School, Southview Middle School, Ankeny Centennial High School, and Ankeny High School.

Great job, students! Way to represent Ankeny Schools! üçé

Read more about what these students took part in here: http://ow.ly/hWqH50zU5AW

Today parents received a text message asking them to fill out a survey if you DO NOT have internet access at home.

If you do have internet access, no further action is necessary.

FAQ:
Why was this sent via text? So you would not need an internet connection to respond to the survey

Why does the district need this information? The district purchased hot spots to help provide internet connectivity to those students who are in need.

I didn't get the text, what do I do? Please contact Jennifer Riedemann at Jennifer.riedemann@ankenyschools.org

Handouts will be given with the material pickup on Monday, with the code for surveys available in Spanish, Vietnamese, and Bosnian.

Another group of people who deserve to be celebrated are our district leaders. From principals to district administrators to the school board, these people have put in countless hours the last two months to ensure the plans put in place are the very best for Ankeny students.

Principals and district administrators have mobilized our staff of around 1,700 employees to continue serving students.

Our school board has had twice the number of meetings they typically do in a month to ensure our staff and students are taken care of.

However hard you think this group is working, double it and that is probably how much time they've been putting in. So to our leaders who work as long and hard as it takes to do what's best for kids, THANK YOU! #AnkenySchools #OneAnkeny #ThankYouPrincipals #ThankYouAdministrators #ThankYouSchoolBoard

Did you know our nurses organized QUICKLY to help get students any needed medications when the school closures began? And that our counselors and social workers have been pulling together community resources for families (Found here: https://bit.ly/3aOnQqS) and checking in with families the school hasn't heard from recently? On top of all this, they are also getting ready for next school year! Let's tell our counselors, social workers, and nurses how much WE APPRECIATE them! Thanks for taking care of our students minds, bodies, and hearts!

Also, it is important to note that if your student needs anything during this time that the school district can support you in, please don't hesitate to contact your school's counselor, social worker, and/or nurse. They are all still working and ready to provide support!

Ankeny Schools will provide an opportunity for free breakfast and lunch for children under the age of 18. This will start Monday, March 23 and go through April 8. The district will provide one free pre-packed breakfast and lunch per day, per child under 18.

On Monday, each child under 18 will receive breakfast/lunch for Monday & Tuesday; On Wednesday, each child under 18 will receive breakfast/lunch for Wednesday, Thursday and Friday.

Please stay in your vehicles when you come to pick up your meals. Our staff will place the meals in your trunk or backseat.

When & Where: Monday‚Äôs & Wednesday‚Äôs from 12:00 p.m. - 1:00 p.m. Crocker Elementary, East Elementary, and Southeast Elementary. post_text: Polk County Iowa Supervisor Steve VanOort recently presented Ankeny Schools Superintendent Dr. Bruce A. Kimpston and Nurse Mandy Snyder with a Community Betterment Grant. The grant will be used to purchase a new vision screener that the Ankeny Community School District's team of nurses can use to test students. The new device is an easy and efficient way to check students' vision and can detect amblyopia (lazy eye) risk factors. This screener is an improvement from the box screeners that have been used.
text: Polk County Iowa Supervisor Steve VanOort recently presented Ankeny Schools Superintendent Dr. Bruce A. Kimpston and Nurse Mandy Snyder with a Community Betterment Grant. The grant will be used to purchase a new vision screener that the Ankeny Community School District's team of nurses can use to test students. The new device is an easy and efficient way to check students' vision and can detect amblyopia (lazy eye) risk factors. This screener is an improvement from the box screeners that have been used.

post_text: TBT - so cool! Check this out from the archives! The photo was taken after the Ankeny tornado in 1974. Look closely, you can see the damage done to the buildings. The district office and Neveln buildings are still in use today. Central School was torn down after the tornado and was located where the Ankeny Historical Society barn and house are now (the corner of SW 3rd and SW School St.). The drawings are of Central, that no longer exists.
